lis]], compilers, Turing Award (1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amturing.acm.org/award_winners/perlis_0132439.cfm|title=A. J. Perlis|date=|author=David Nofre|publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery]] (ACM)}}</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Rabiner]], [[Digital signal processing]], [[Speech processing]]\n* [[Frank Rosenblatt]], invented an artificial intelligence program called \"[[Frank Rosenblatt#Perceptron|Perceptrons]]\" (1960)<ref name=\"Hyping Artificial Intelligence, Yet Again\">{{cite magazine|title=Hyping Artificial Intelligence, Yet Again|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/hyping-artificial-intelligence-yet-again|magazine= The New Yorker}}</ref>\n* [[Azriel Rosenfeld]], [[image analysis]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2004/02/27/azriel-rosenfeld-dies-at-73/572122c6-a7dd-46d1-a8d6-36e783587eae/|title=Azriel Rosenfeld Dies at 73|date=Feb 27, 2004|author=Patricia Sullivan|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n* [[Bruce Schneier]], cryptographer, author, founder of [[BT Managed Security Solutions|Counterpane Internet Security, Inc.]]\n* [[Ben Shneiderman]], human-computer interaction, information visualization<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/186539/the-jewish-inspiration-that-guided-photographers-o/|title=The Jewish Inspiration That Guided Photographers of Magnum|date=Nov 3, 2013|author=Menachem Wecker|publisher=[[The Forward]]}}</ref>\n* [[Herbert A. Simon]], cognitive and computer scientist, Turing Award (1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amturing.acm.org/award_winners/simon_1031467.cfm|title=Herbert (\"Herb\") Alexander Simon|author=Hunter Heyck|publisher=[[Association for Computing Machinery]] (ACM)}}</ref>\n* [[Abraham Sinkov]], cryptanalyst, [[NSA Hall of Honor]] (1999)\n* [[Gustave Solomon]], [[mathematician]] and [[electrical engineer]] who was one of the founders of the algebraic theory of [[error detection and correction]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/1997/07/code-warriors-fought-errors-byte-by-byte/|title=Code Warriors Fought Errors Byte by Byte|date=Jul 16, 1997|author=Steve Silberman|magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|author-link=Steve Silberman}}</ref><ref name=\"Gustave Solomon, Mathematician, Is Dead at 65\">{{cite news|title=Gustave Solomon, Mathematician, Is Dead at 65|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/18/us/gustave-solomon-mathematician-is-dead-at-65.html|newspaper= [[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Solomonoff]], algorithmic information theory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.jewishcurrents.org/tag/ray-solomonoff/|title=A Pioneer of Artificial Intelligence|date=Jul 24, 2017|author=Lawrence Bush|publisher=[[Jewish Currents]]}}</ref>\n* [[Richard Stallman]], designed the [[GNU]] operating system, founder of the [[Free Software Foundation]] (FSF)\n* [[Andrew S. Tanenbaum]], American-Dutch computer scientist, creator of [[MINIX]]\n* [[Warren Teitelman]], autocorrect, [[Undo|Undo/Redo]], [[Interlisp]]\n* [[Jeffrey Ullman]], compilers, theory of computation, data-structures, databases, awarded [[Knuth Prize]] (2000)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mondoweiss.net/2011/01/world-renowned-computer-scientist-suffers-harrowing-mid-air-iq-drop/|title=World-renowned computer scientist suffers harrowing mid-air IQ drop|date=Jan 14, 2011|author=Philip Weiss|publisher=[[Mondoweiss]]|author-link=Philip Weiss}}</ref>\n* [[Peter J. Weinberger]], contributed to the design of the [[AWK programming language]] (he is the \"W\" in AWK), and the [[Fortran|FORTRAN]] compiler [[Fortran#FORTRAN 77|FORTRAN 77]]<ref name=\"reader\">{{cite techreport |first1=M. D. |last1=McIlroy |authorlink1=Doug McIlroy |year=1987 |url=http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~doug/reader.pdf |title=A Research Unix reader: annotated excerpts from the Programmer's Manual, 1971\u20131986 |series=CSTR |number=139 |institution=Bell Labs}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Weizenbaum]], German-born computer scientist; developer of [[ELIZA]]; the [[Weizenbaum Award]] is named after him<ref>{{cite web|url