ise]]\n*[[Power, West Virginia|Power]]\n*[[Rabbit Hill, West Virginia|Rabbit Hill]]\n*[[Rockdale, West Virginia|Rockdale]]\n*[[Short Creek, West Virginia|Short Creek]]\n*[[Virginville, West Virginia|Virginville]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brooke Hills Playhouse]]\n* [[Castleman Run Lake Wildlife Management Area]]\n* [[Cross Creek Wildlife Management Area]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Brooke County, West Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brookewv.org/ Official Brooke County Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051124024623/http://boe.broo.k12.wv.us/ Brooke County Schools]\n*[http://wellsburg.lib.wv.us/ Brooke County Public Library]\n*[http://www.brookewv.org/bceda.html Brooke County Economic Development Homepage]\n*[http://www.topofwv.com/ Top of WV CVB, the Convention & Visitors Bureau for Brooke and Hancock Counties]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Brooke County, West Virginia\n|North     = [[Hancock County, West Virginia|Hancock County]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Washington County, Pennsylvania]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[Ohio County, West Virginia|Ohio County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Jefferson County, Ohio]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Brooke County, West Virginia}}\n{{Northern Panhandle of West Virginia}}\n{{West Virginia}}\n\n{{coord|40.27|-80.58|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-WV_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Brooke County, West Virginia| ]]\n[[Category:West Virginia counties on the Ohio River]]\n[[Category:Counties of Appalachia]]\n[[Category:1797 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitics:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooke_County,_West_Virginia"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates  <br />\n(as of 10 February){{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = {{ubl|[[Dubai]]|[[Abu Dhabi]]}}\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = January 29, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 61<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alfaham |first1=Tariq |last2=Bashir |first2=Hassan |title=41 new COVID-19 cases, three recoveries in UAE, distance learning extended until end of school year |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302833986 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Wam |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 8<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last1=Mohamed |first1=Hatem |last2=Alfaham |first2=Tariq |title=Ministry of Health announces 150 new cases of COVID-19, two deaths among various nationalities |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834368 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Wam |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 814 (as of 1 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 753<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 2<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.mohap.gov.ae/en/AwarenessCenter/Pages/COVID-19.aspx\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). \"https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html\" ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after being cured. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old Chinese woman who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after being cured.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of Covid-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including 3 Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/20/world/middleeast/20reuters-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally.html|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were 7 recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, 7 recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. the TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> 4 new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with 7 recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and 3 recovery cases were confirmed.All of the 72 cases are said to be in stable health condition and receiving necessary treatment. They include one person from each of Sri Lanka, Jordan, Palestine, Syria, Iran, Comoros, China, Saudi Arabia, Kyrgyzstan, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia, Greece, Uruguay, Romania, Sweden, South Africa, Iraq, Yemen and two persons from each of Nepal and Ethiopia.They also involve four Emiratis, five Britons, five Pakistanis, five Lebanese and eight Bangladeshis in addition to 23 Indians. Three more COVID-19 patients (a Pakistani citizen and two Bangladeshis) have made full recovery, the ministry added, taking to 55 the total number of cured patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now 5. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to 6. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention has announced 150 new coronavirus cases on Wednesday, April 1. The total number of cases in the country stands at 814 now. The ministry also announced two deaths due to Covid-19. One is a 62-year-old Asian national, and the other a 78-year-old Arab national \u2013 both suffered from chronic diseases and heart condition, which led to the deterioration of their health. The total number of death so far is eight. The new patients contracted the virus from previously diagnosed cases, and by not adhering to preventive measures and social distancing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref> https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref> https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|United Arab Emirates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates  <br />\n(as of 10 February){{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = {{ubl|[[Dubai]]|[[Abu Dhabi]]}}\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = January 29, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 61<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alfaham |first1=Tariq |last2=Bashir |first2=Hassan |title=41 new COVID-19 cases, three recoveries in UAE, distance learning extended until end of school year |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302833986 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Wam |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 8<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last1=Mohamed |first1=Hatem |last2=Alfaham |first2=Tariq |title=Ministry of Health announces 150 new cases of COVID-19, two deaths among various nationalities |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834368 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=Wam |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 814 (as of 1 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 753<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 2<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.mohap.gov.ae/en/AwarenessCenter/Pages/COVID-19.aspx\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). \"https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html\" ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after being cured. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old woman of a Chinese national who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after being cured.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of Covid-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including 3 Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/20/world/middleeast/20reuters-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally.html|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were 7 recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, 7 recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. the TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> 4 new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with 7 recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and 3 recovery cases were confirmed.All of the 72 cases are said to be in stable health condition and receiving necessary treatment. They include one person from each of Sri Lanka, Jordan, Palestine, Syria, Iran, Comoros, China, Saudi Arabia, Kyrgyzstan, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Serbia, Greece, Uruguay, Romania, Sweden, South Africa, Iraq, Yemen and two persons from each of Nepal and Ethiopia.They also involve four Emiratis, five Britons, five Pakistanis, five Lebanese and eight Bangladeshis in addition to 23 Indians. Three more COVID-19 patients (a Pakistani citizen and two Bangladeshis) have made full recovery, the ministry added, taking to 55 the total number of cured patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now 5. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to 6. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention has announced 150 new coronavirus cases on Wednesday, April 1. The total number of cases in the country stands at 814 now.The ministry also announced two deaths due to Covid-19. One is a 62-year-old Asian national, and the other a 78-year-old Arab national - both suffered from chronic diseases and heart condition, which led to the deterioration of their health. The total number of death so far is eight. The new patients contracted the virus from previously diagnosed cases, and by not adhering to preventive measures and social distancing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref> https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref> https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{