{"title_page": "Nigeria women's national under-20 football team", "text_new": "{{For|the men's team|Nigeria national under-20 football team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n|  Name               = Nigeria Under-20 \n| Badge              = \n| Badge_size         = 230px\n|  FIFA Trigramme     = NGA\n|  Nickname           = ''Falconets''\n|  Association        = [[Nigeria Football Federation]]\n|  Confederation      = [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] (Africa)\n|  Sub-confederation  = [[West Africa Football Union|WAFU]] (West Africa)\n|  Coach              = [[Christopher Danjuma]]\n|  Asst Manager       = \n|  Captain            = \n|  Most caps          = \n|  Top scorer         = \n| pattern_la1        = _ngra18h\n| pattern_b1         = _nga18h\n| pattern_ra1        = _ngra18h\n| pattern_sh1        = _nga18h\n| pattern_so1        = _nga18h\n| leftarm1           = 008000\n| body1              = 008000\n| rightarm1          = 008000\n| shorts1            = FFFFFF\n| socks1             = 37FF5D\n| pattern_la2        = _ngra18a\n| pattern_b2         = _ngra18a\n| pattern_ra2        = _ngra18a\n| pattern_sh2        = _ngra18a\n| pattern_so2        = _nga18a\n| leftarm2           = 1A4030\n| body2              = 1A4030\n| rightarm2          = 1A4030\n| shorts2            = 1A4030\n| socks2             = 1A4030\n| First game         = {{fbwu|20|NGA}} 6\u20130 {{fbwu-rt|20|MLI}} <br />([[Nigeria]]; 7 April 2002)\n| Largest win        = {{fbwu|20|NGA}} 10\u20130 {{fbwu-rt|20|SLE}} <br />(Nigeria; 2014)\n| Largest loss       = {{fbwu|20|JPN}} 6\u20130 {{fbwu-rt|20|NGA}} <br />([[Port Moresby]], [[Papua New Guinea]]; 13 November 2016)\n| World cup apps     = \n| World cup first    = \n| World cup best     = \n| Regional name      = [[FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]]\n| Regional cup apps  = 9\n| Regional cup first = [[2002 FIFA U-19 Women's World Championship|2002]]\n| Regional cup best  = Runners-up ([[2010 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup|2010]],  [[2014 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup|2014]])\n| 2ndRegional name      = [[African U-20 Women's World Cup qualification|African U-20 World Cup qualification]]\n| 2ndRegional cup apps  = 9\n| 2ndRegional cup first = [[2002 African U-19 Women's Championship|2002]]\n| 2ndRegional cup best  = Champions ([[2002 African U-19 Women's Championship|2002]], [[2004 African U-19 Women's Championship|2004]])\n| type = women\n}}\nThe '''Nigeria women's national under-20 football team''', nicknamed the '''Falconets''', represents Nigeria in international youth women's football competitions. Its primary role is the development of players in preparation for the senior [[Nigeria women's national football team|women's national team]]. The team competes in a variety of competitions, including the biennial [[FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]] and [[African U-20 Women's World Cup qualification]], which is the top competitions for this age group. \n\nThe team as qualified for every edition of the [[FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]] and have been runners-up twice, losing to [[Germany women's national under-20 football team| Germany]] on both occasions in [[2010 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup|2010]] and [[2014 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup|2014]].\n==Competitive record==\n===FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup record===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!colspan=10|[[FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Result\n!Matches\n!Wins\n!Draws*\n!Losses\n!GF\n!GA\n|- bgcolor=\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[2002 FIFA U-19 Women's World Championship|2002]]||Group stage||3||0||1||2||2||5\n|-\n|{{flagicon|THA}} [[2004 FIFA U-19 Women's World Championship|2004]]||Quarter-finals||4||1||2||1||5||5\n|- bgcolor=\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[2006 FIFA U-20 Women's World Championship|2006]]||Quarter-finals||4||2||0||2||13||6\n|- bgcolor=\n|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[2008 FIFA U-20 Women's World Cup|2008]]||Quarter-finals||4||2||2||2||8||5\n|- bgcolor=silver\n|{{flagicon|GER}} [[